onRevisions","id":"85546","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/85546"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 4-year-old boy is brought to the emergency department by his single parent. The parent explains that while giving the child a shower, they left briefly to answer the door. During this time, the child allegedly turned on the hot water and started crying. The child has severe pain and is distressed during examination. Physical examination reveals blisters and erythematous skin involving the lower limbs up to the waist.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following burn patterns is most suspicious for non-accidental injury?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Asymmetric distribution","Involvement of skin folds","Sharp linear demarcation line","Noncircumferential pattern","Variable burn depth"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Esharp linear demarcation line\u003C/strong\u003E between burned and normal skin is highly suspicious for intentional immersion burns, a common form of non-accidental injury. This pattern occurs when a child is deliberately lowered into hot water to a specific level.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other patterns are more typical of accidental burns:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAsymmetric distribution\u003C/strong\u003E - Common in accidental splash or spill burns\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInvolvement of skin folds\u003C/strong\u003E - Typical of accidental scalds where water flows into natural creases\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENoncircumferential pattern\u003C/strong\u003E - Usually seen with accidental contact or splash burns\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVariable burn depth\u003C/strong\u003E - Characteristic of accidental spills where water flows down the body\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the history of a shower accident is inconsistent with the burn pattern observed. Accidental shower scalds typically show irregular patterns with splash marks and varying depths, starting from the point of contact (usually upper body) and becoming more superficial lower down. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Immersion burns with clear linear demarcation lines are highly suspicious for non-accidental injury in children","Accidental hot water burns typically show splash marks and irregular patterns","Inconsistency between the reported mechanism of injury and burn pattern is a red flag for abuse"],"references":["Toon M, Maybauer D, Arceneaux L, Fraser J, Meyer W, Runge A et al. Children with burn injuries-assessment of trauma, neglect, violence and abuse. Journal of Injury and Violence Research. 2011;3(2):99-111.","Smith A. Nonaccidental injury in childhood. Aust Fam Physician. 2011;40(11):858-864. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/5cbf2ff1-a135-43e1-8dbd-837743bb29bf/Nonaccidental-injury-in-childhood.aspx","Tran S, Jacques MA, Holland AJA. Assessment and management of minor burns in children. Aust J Gen Pract. 2019;48(9):584-589. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2019/september/minor-burns-in-children-2"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69838"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2345"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69838","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/69838"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-16T19:40:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-16T19:41:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2345"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85546"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emo